statement.p:
The wedge product dx\wedge dy is the signed area measurement defined by
\boxed{(dx\wedge dy)(\mathbf u,\mathbf v)=dx(\mathbf u)dy(\mathbf v)-dy(\mathbf u)dx(\mathbf v).}
If
\mathbf u=(u_1,u_2),\qquad \mathbf v=(v_1,v_2),
then
\boxed{(dx\wedge dy)(\mathbf u,\mathbf v)=u_1v_2-u_2v_1.}

subsection.p:
The sign rule is immediate:
\boxed{dx\wedge dy=-dy\wedge dx.}
Also,
\boxed{dx\wedge dx=0,\qquad dy\wedge dy=0.}
A vector and itself span no area.

Now compute the cross product:
\mathbf u\times\mathbf v\amp=(2,1,3)\times(1,4,0) \amp=(1\cdot0-3\cdot4,\;3\cdot1-2\cdot0,\;2\cdot4-1\cdot1) \amp=(-12,3,7).
So the cross product has been secretly collecting the three signed shadow areas: \boxed{\mathbf u\times\mathbf v=\bigl((dy\wedge dz)(\mathbf u,\mathbf v),\,(dz\wedge dx)(\mathbf u,\mathbf v),\,(dx\wedge dy)(\mathbf u,\mathbf v)\bigr).}

So the wedge product is not a new trick for multiplying symbols. It is a way to keep
track of oriented geometry:
\text{length, area, volume, and the signs that come from order.}
